<p>
<term>Gaussian elimination for equations with no or infinitely many solutions:</term>
The first step is always to get the augmented matrix into REF. Once you've done this, here's how 
to tell how many solutions there are, and what to do next.
<ul>
<li>
<p>If in REF we have a row of the form
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{cccc} 0 \amp  0 \amp  \dots \amp 0 \amp  b
\end{amatrix}
</me>
where <m>b</m> is nonzero, then we conclude that there are no solutions. This is because it is 
impossible for <m>0x_1 + 0x_2 + \dots + 0x_n</m> to equal something nonzero.</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>Look for any columns such that all its entries are not the leading entries of any row. 
(This can occur if there are less equations than the number of variables, or if there is a zero 
row in REF.) If there are any, then you will need to assign these variables to a parameter. 
For example, consider the REF augmented matrix
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  8 \amp  0 \amp  1\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  2\\
\end{amatrix}
</me>
Then the <m>z</m>-column doesn't contain any leading entries, so we introduce the parameter <m>t \in \R</m>, and let <m>z=t</m>. Now solve for the rest of the variables in terms of the parameter. There will be infinitely many solutions (one for each value of the parameter).</p>
</li>
<li>
<p>If neither of the two above situations apply, then there is a unique solution, and we can solve for it as usual.</p>
</li>
</ul>
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-no-sols">
<statement>
<p>Show that the system of linear equations
<me>
\begin{cases}
  x + 4y -z    \amp  = 0 \\
  x + 6y       \amp  = 3 \\
  2x + 10y - z \amp  = 5
\end{cases}
</me>.
has no solutions.
</p>
<p>
Row reducing gives
<md>
<mrow>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  4 \amp  -1 \amp  0\\
  1 \amp  6 \amp  0 \amp  3\\
  2 \amp  10 \amp  -1 \amp  5\\
\end{amatrix}
\amp\xrightarrow[R_3\mapsto R_3 - 2R_1]{R_2 \mapsto R_2 - R_1} 
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  4 \amp  -1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  3\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  5
\end{amatrix}
\\
\amp\xrightarrow{R_3 \mapsto R_3 - R_2}                        
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  1 \amp  4 \amp  -1 \amp  0\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  1 \amp  3\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  2
\end{amatrix}
</mrow>
</md>.
The last row is a zero row with 2 after the line, so there is no solution.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
The next example shows how to solve linear equations with infinitely many solutions, by introducing 
a parameter. In this example, we will only need to introduce one parameter. Sometimes it is necessary 
to introduce multiple parameters; this will be covered later in <xref ref="ex-multparam"/>.
</p>


<example xml:id="ex-inftysolns">
<statement>
<p>
Solve the system of linear equations
<me>
\begin{cases}
  2x + y +5z  \amp  = 1 \\
  2x + 3y +4z \amp  = 4 \\
  4x + 11 z   \amp  = -1
\end{cases}
</me>.
has no solutions.
</p>
<p>
Row reducing gives
<me>
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  2 \amp  1 \amp  5 \amp  1\\
  2 \amp  3 \amp  4 \amp  4\\
  4 \amp  0 \amp  11 \amp  -1\\
\end{amatrix}
\to
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  2 \amp  1 \amp  5 \amp  1\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  -1 \amp  3\\
  0 \amp  -2 \amp  1 \amp  -3
\end{amatrix}
\to
\begin{amatrix}{ccc}
  2 \amp  1 \amp  5 \amp  1\\
  0 \amp  2 \amp  -1 \amp  3\\
  0 \amp  0 \amp  0 \amp  0
\end{amatrix}
</me>.
The last column has no leading entries, so <m>z</m> is not determined. However, this is fine: 
we let <m>z = t</m>, for <m>t \in \R</m> a parameter. Now we can back-substitute in terms 
of <m>t</m>. We have <m>2y - z = 3</m>, so <m>y = \frac{1}{2}(3+z) = \frac{3}{2} + \frac{1}{2}t</m>. 
Finally,
<md>
<mrow>
2x + y +5z = 1 \implies x \amp  = \frac{1}{2}(1-y - 5z)                                               \\
\amp  = \frac{1}{2}\Bigl(1 - \Bigl(\frac{3}{2}+\frac{1}{2}t\Bigr) -5t\Bigr) \\
\amp  = -\frac{1}{4}-\frac{11}{4}t
</mrow>
</md>.
So there are infinitely many solutions 
<m>[x, y, z] = [-\frac{1}{4}-\frac{11}{4}t, \frac{3}{2} + \frac{1}{2}t, t]</m>, <m>t \in \R</m>.
</p>
</statement>
</example>

<p>
A geometric interpretation of <xref ref="ex-inftysolns"/> is that the 3 planes intersect in the line
<me>
\vect{x} = \Bigl[-\frac{1}{4}, \frac{3}{2}, 0\Bigr] + t\Bigl[-\frac{11}{4}, \frac{1}{2}, 1\Bigr], \qquad t\in \R
</me>.
Notice that to save space and time, we didn't label the arrows during row reduction. We will sometimes 
do the same thing in future examples.
</p>


